# 01 — UAMI + GitHub OIDC federated credentials

> **Owner: central platform / platform-engineering team.** This creates a
> user-assigned managed identity (UAMI) for the pilot's prod deploy and
> federates it to GitHub Actions via OIDC — **no client secret is ever created**.

Onboarding path: **{{ONBOARDING_PATH}}** · posture: **{{POSTURE}}** · platform: **GitHub Actions**

## What gets created
- UAMI `{{UAMI_NAME}}` in resource group `{{UAMI_RESOURCE_GROUP}}`.
- Two federated credentials on that UAMI:
  - environment `{{ENV_NAME}}` deploys → subject `{{FED_SUBJECT_ENV}}`
  - `main` branch → subject `{{FED_SUBJECT_MAIN}}`

## Commands
```bash
# 1) Create the user-assigned managed identity
az identity create \
  --name {{UAMI_NAME}} \
  --resource-group {{UAMI_RESOURCE_GROUP}} \
  --subscription {{UAMI_SUBSCRIPTION_ID}}

# 2) Federate to GitHub Actions (OIDC) — environment deploys
az identity federated-credential create \
  --name gh-{{REPO_SLUG}}-env-{{ENV_NAME}} \
  --identity-name {{UAMI_NAME}} \
  --resource-group {{UAMI_RESOURCE_GROUP}} \
  --issuer https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com \
  --subject {{FED_SUBJECT_ENV}} \
  --audiences api://AzureADTokenExchange

# 3) Federate the main branch (provision dry-runs / drift checks)
az identity federated-credential create \
  --name gh-{{REPO_SLUG}}-main \
  --identity-name {{UAMI_NAME}} \
  --resource-group {{UAMI_RESOURCE_GROUP}} \
  --issuer https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com \
  --subject {{FED_SUBJECT_MAIN}} \
  --audiences api://AzureADTokenExchange
```

## Hand back to the pilot team
- The UAMI **client id**:
  `az identity show -n {{UAMI_NAME}} -g {{UAMI_RESOURCE_GROUP}} --query clientId -o tsv`
  Put it in the workflow `AZURE_CLIENT_ID` (replace `REPLACE_WITH_UAMI_CLIENT_ID`)
  or store it as a repository variable.
- Grant RBAC next: see `02-rbac-role-assignments.md`.
